      Block trades
   =20
 =20
Earlier this year, Morgan Stanley got in trouble for leaking some block tra=
des. Big shareholders (private equity funds, etc.) in public companies woul=
d come to Morgan Stanley to say =E2=80=9Cwe would like to sell our XYZ stoc=
k today, we will ask you for a bid this afternoon, get to work preparing yo=
ur bid, but whatever you do don=E2=80=99t tell anyone else about this.=E2=
=80=9D And then Morgan Stanley=E2=80=99s head of equity syndicate, Pawan Pa=
ssi, would call his buddies at a few hedge funds and say =E2=80=9Cwe have a=
 block of XYZ stock coming, get ready,=E2=80=9D and the hedge funds would s=
hort the stock and make money (because the block trade would lower the stoc=
k price), while the big shareholder would lose money (because the short sal=
es would also lower the stock price and result in a lower price for the blo=
ck).Eventually US regulators discovered this and concluded that it was bad:=
 Morgan Stanley had material nonpublic information (its clients=E2=80=99 bl=
ock-trade plans), it had an obligation to keep that information confidentia=
l (the clients told it not to tell anyone, and it agreed), and it leaked th=
e information to the hedge funds so that they could trade. That looks a bit=
 like=C2=A0insider trading. So the US Securities and Exchange Commission an=
d federal prosecutors brought charges, fined Morgan Stanley a lot of money =
and barred Passi from the securities industry for a year. (Amazingly, he th=
en went to work at one of the hedge funds that he had tipped off =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0though it converted into a family office, possibly so that he could w=
ork there despite his industry ban.)=C2=A0But the hedge funds that Passi ti=
pped off =E2=80=94=C2=A0the ones who actually traded on his information =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0never got in trouble. It=E2=80=99s a little weird. But I think =
the best analysis is something like: Passi (and thus Morgan Stanley)=C2=A0k=
new=C2=A0that he was doing the wrong thing. He had the=C2=A0information, he=
=C2=A0knew it was confidential (because the client told him directly), he k=
new the hedge funds would trade, and he leaked it anyway. The hedge funds d=
idn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0necessarily=C2=A0know that. They could have thought, not=
 =E2=80=9CMorgan Stanley is betraying its client=C2=A0by leaking this infor=
mation to me,=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9CMorgan Stanley is=C2=A0helping=
=C2=A0its client by trying to line up buyers for the block trade, and since=
 they didn=E2=80=99t tell me not to pre-hedge, I=E2=80=99m going to do that=
.=E2=80=9D As far as the hedge funds knew, maybe, Morgan Stanley was=C2=A0s=
upposed=C2=A0to be telling them about the block trade as part of its market=
ing, and they were free to trade.This analysis is a little suspect =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s not usually how block trades work? =E2=80=94=C2=A0a=
nd it is complicated by the fact that some of the hedge funds would tell Pa=
ssi things like =E2=80=9CI know who my daddy is=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C[I] w=
ould be at the kiddie table if it wasn=E2=80=99t for [Passi].=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=9CYou don=E2=80=99t say =E2=80=98I know who my daddy is=E2=80=99 to you=
r salesperson unless you know you are getting some sort of weird personal f=
avor,=E2=80=9D I wrote. But maybe that=E2=80=99s wrong; maybe it meant, lik=
e, =E2=80=9Cthank you for including me in your entirely legitimate marketin=
g process.=E2=80=9DAnyway the weird upshot of all of this is that one of th=
ose hedge fund traders, Robert Gagliardi, is suing his subsequent employer,=
 Evolution Capital Management, for a $7.5 million bonus that he says it owe=
s him. Evolution has said that it can=E2=80=99t pay him the bonus because o=
f his =E2=80=9Cdisreputable conduct,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Csaid in filings =
last month that it believed Gagliardi was the unnamed investor referenced b=
y the SEC and US Department of Justice in January.=E2=80=9D Specifically it=
 thinks he=E2=80=99s the =E2=80=9CI know who my daddy is=E2=80=9D guy:The e=
xtracts Evolution selected included one from a DoJ document in which an unn=
amed investor, which the hedge fund said it believed was Gagliardi, referre=
d to Passi as his =E2=80=9Cdaddy=E2=80=9D who had =E2=80=9Cput [him] in the=
 =E2=80=A6 game=E2=80=9D on block trades. Another extract from the document=
 described an investor betting against Canada Goose after talking to a Morg=
an Stanley banker who asked, =E2=80=9Chow is your store of cold weather jac=
kets?=E2=80=9D, and =E2=80=9Cchuckled=E2=80=9D.He does not exactly deny the=
 =E2=80=9Cdaddy=E2=80=9D comment, but he does say he did nothing wrong:Gagl=
iardi said in his latest court filing, dated July 12, that he would =E2=80=
=9Cproceed on the assumed basis that those extracts refer to him=E2=80=9D, =
but that Evolution=E2=80=99s inclusion of them in its court filings was =E2=
=80=9Cabusive=E2=80=9D and part of a =E2=80=9Csmear campaign=E2=80=9D, and =
that no regulator had ever accused him of wrongdoing. =E2=80=A6He said none=
 of the authorities=E2=80=99 documents =E2=80=9Cmakes any allegation of wro=
ngdoing against=E2=80=9D the investor or alleges =E2=80=9Cdisreputable cond=
uct=E2=80=9D or that the person in question =E2=80=9Cknowingly used confide=
ntial information to obtain any unfair market advantage=E2=80=9D.He said th=
e SEC had =E2=80=9Cconfirmed expressly=E2=80=9D in a letter dated March 4 t=
hat =E2=80=9Con the basis of the matters to date it does not recommend that=
 any action be taken=E2=80=9D against him. An SEC spokesperson declined to =
comment.Yes right he apparently traded on an illegal tip, but=C2=A0his=C2=
=A0trading wasn=E2=80=99t illegal, so it=E2=80=99s not a reason to deny him=
 a bonus.=C2=A0
