      Diversification
   =20
 =20
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Layan Odeh and Dinesh Nair have a profile of Conno=
r Teskey, the potential future chief executive officer of Brookfield Asset =
Management, which discusses Brookfield=E2=80=99s somewhat odd corporate str=
ucture. A lot of financial firms are partnerships owned by their executives=
, and a lot of financial firms are public companies, and a fair number of f=
inancial firms are public companies that want to promote a partnership cult=
ure and whose executives own a lot of stock. But Brookfield maybe goes furt=
her than most in being public but also a partnership:The Brookfield way ext=
ends to a compensation system that has churned out multimillionaires and bi=
llionaires. Unlike other alternative-asset managers that reward senior exec=
utives with carried interest, Brookfield prefers to award stock. For rising=
 executives, significant equity awards cement their devotion to the firm. A=
nd for long-timers, their swelling stakes give them a big incentive to stay=
.In a somewhat unusual structure, the firm has two classes of shares: Class=
 A stock that=E2=80=99s publicly traded and gives owners the right to vote =
for half the board, and class B stock that=E2=80=99s held only by current a=
nd former insiders who elect the other half.The idea is that the =E2=80=9Cp=
artners=E2=80=9D act as the stewards of B shares and commit to investing la=
rge portions of their wealth in A shares, ensuring stability. ...The result=
 is that the firm=E2=80=99s top five executives each hold stock worth billi=
ons. The A shares that [current CEO Bruce] Flatt owns directly in Brookfiel=
d and BAM =E2=80=94 disclosed in regulatory filings =E2=80=94 are worth wel=
l over $3 billion, and that doesn=E2=80=99t include other holdings tied to =
the company. One person close to the company estimated that, further down, =
about 10 employees have a net worth of around $300 million apiece, and that=
 15 more have roughly $100 million.The way you get to $300 million of Brook=
field stock is mostly by being=C2=A0granted=C2=A0the stock as part of your =
compensation. But you can always buy a little extra:Piling up stock is seen=
 as a virtue. When Flatt noticed a staffer clutching a Starbucks cup in the=
 elevator, he asked how much it cost, and =E2=80=94 after some quick mental=
 math =E2=80=94 suggested the employee drop their daily ritual and use the =
money to buy two more shares a month and drink the coffee available for fre=
e in the office.=E2=80=9CCut out your daily Starbucks so you can buy a hous=
e=E2=80=9D is probably the most controversial personal finance advice, but =
=E2=80=9Ccut out your daily Starbucks so you can buy more shares in your em=
ployer=E2=80=9D is even weirder. Your human capital is tied to your employe=
r, you=E2=80=99re getting paid in stock,=C2=A0and=C2=A0you have to put all =
your free cash into more stock?
