      Fusion
   =20
 =20
One possible analysis of Sam Altman is that many of his science-fiction-y p=
lans are far-fetched and overhyped and he won=E2=80=99t really build artifi=
cial general intelligence or commercial fusion reactors. But that is boring=
, and I think it is more fun to assume that everything is 100% real and thi=
nk about incentives and governance. Like:=09Sam Altman is the chief executi=
ve officer of OpenAI, which is =E2=80=94=C2=A0let=E2=80=99s assume =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0moments away from making superintelligent robots that could usher =
humanity into a world of abundance and/or enslave us all.=09It is very very=
 very important that the robots usher in abundance rather than enslaving us=
 all.=09A superintelligent-robot-builder who was motivated by money might b=
e tempted to build enslaving robots rather than abundance robots, for somew=
hat underspecified financial reasons.=09More seriously, a superintelligent-=
robot-builder who was motivated by money might=C2=A0hoard the robots, provi=
ding a lot of abundance for people willing to pay a lot for robots, but no =
abundance for anyone else.=09Therefore, it is important for OpenAI=E2=80=99=
s motives to be pure. So it is structured as a nonprofit, and its =E2=80=9C=
principal beneficiary is humanity, not OpenAI investors.=E2=80=9D Even thou=
gh =09=09it has investors who expect to make a lot of money, weird.=09Altma=
n himself owns no equity in OpenAI, so that his motives can be pure: He bui=
lds the robots for humanity, not for the money.=09However! A world of super=
intelligent robot abundance will require certain inputs.=09Mainly (1) micro=
chips, (2) electric power and (3) text to train models.=09And Altman is fre=
e to invest in all of those selling-picks-and-shovels businesses.=C2=A0=09P=
referably in as futuristic and sci-fi a way as possible: Not, like, buying =
stock in California electric utilities, but funding nuclear fusion startups=
.=09In his role as CEO of OpenAI, Altman is obligated to provide the robots=
 to humanity in a responsible, fair, abundance-promoting way.=09But he can =
absolutely gouge them on electricity, that=E2=80=99s no problem at all.Now =
that I have typed it all out I realize it doesn=E2=80=99t make that much se=
nse. Still it=E2=80=99s a good dumb sci-fi plot. Everyone has a superintell=
igent robot, but the guy who invented the robots controls the electricity. =
Anyway:Sam Altman, the billionaire chief executive officer of OpenAI, is st=
aking a sizable chunk of his personal wealth on a startup chasing the holy =
grail of nuclear fusion =E2=80=93 the elusive, theoretically limitless clea=
n-energy source that, he says, is key to an artificial intelligence-enabled=
 future.While other billionaires, including Jeff Bezos, Bill Gates and Geor=
ge Soros, have backed fusion ventures, Altman has made his largest personal=
 investment in Helion Energy, which stands out for its audacious timeline. =
It plans to open the world=E2=80=99s first fusion power plant by 2028 and t=
o supply Microsoft Corp. with energy from it soon after. =E2=80=A6Helion of=
fers little to persuade doubters or skeptics. Though it=E2=80=99s among the=
 best-funded fusion companies, it doesn=E2=80=99t publish experimental resu=
lts or engage in peer review the way large rival startups do, raising red f=
lags in the scientific community.CEO David Kirtley says the main task isn=
=E2=80=99t necessarily publishing =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s building a fusion =
reactor.=E2=80=9CWhen we founded Helion, our goal wasn=E2=80=99t to demonst=
rate interesting new physics,=E2=80=9D Kirtley said in a March interview. =
=E2=80=9CBy iterating and building quickly, you actually learn more than yo=
u ever could if you did a lot of simulation and a lot of computation upfron=
t.=E2=80=9DOpenAI was supposed to be, you know, =E2=80=9Copen=E2=80=9D AI; =
it was supposed to selflessly publish research to improve humanity=E2=80=99=
s understanding of AI, though that goal changed a bit over time. But the fu=
sion company doesn=E2=80=99t care about publishing research; it cares about=
 building a reactor.
