<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Should index funds be illegal?</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/36105007.198391/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9v=
cGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDctMjIvaW5kZXgtZnVuZHMtbWF5LXdvcmstYS1saXR0bGU=
tdG9vLXdlbGw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDcxODI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG=
1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNzE4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0d=
WZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7509d5da" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">know</a> the <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36105007.198391/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMTgtMTItMDcvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYt=
cmVndWxhdG9ycy1hc2staWYtaW5kZXgtZnVuZHMtYXJlLWJhZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzE4MjRfTU9=
ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT=
0yNDA3MTgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB92fbdeec=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">theory</a>: When the same big diversified institutional investors=
 own all of the companies, those companies have less incentive to compete w=
ith each other. If Airline A and Airline B have the same shareholders, and =
Airline A cuts prices to win more market share, that simply hurts the share=
holders: Overall, the airlines sell the same number of tickets but at lower=
 prices.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/36105007.198391/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDItMjEvdGhlLWNvbXBhbmllcy1hcmUtb24tdGhlLXNh=
bWUtdGVhbT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzE4MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9=
zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3MTgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1Zm=
Y/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf40c4fd6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">talk</a> about this theory a <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36105007.198391/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDUtMjEvdGhlLW=
NvbXBhbmllcy13b3JrLWZvci10aGVtc2VsdmVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA3MTgyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJ=
nV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDcxOCZ1=
dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcbc5ef86" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
lot</a>. It is controversial, in part because of disputes about the empiric=
al evidence but mostly, I think, because it doesn=E2=80=99t <em>feel </em>r=
ight. That is:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px=
; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Most large diversif=
ied asset managers do not think this way: They don=E2=80=99t <em>want=C2=A0=
</em>to reduce competition, and they do not go around meeting with the mana=
gers of their portfolio companies to say =E2=80=9Chey you should compete le=
ss.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Most corporate =
executives do not think this way: They don=E2=80=99t care about overall pro=
fits for their shareholders; they care about <em>their</em> company=E2=80=
=99s=C2=A0profits and market share. They care because they are naturally co=
mpetitive people who want to win, but they also care because=C2=A0<em>they=
=C2=A0</em>are not diversified shareholders: The executives themselves own =
a lot of stock in their own firms, so they are motivated to win market shar=
e for themselves.=C2=A0</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So if you thi=
nk this theory is right you will need sort of a better mechanism, one that =
does not rely on the diversified investors actually <em>wanting</em> less=
=C2=A0competition, or on the corporate managers trying to give it to them.<=
a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transp=
arent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a clever one <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36105007.198391/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb=
3JwZ292Lmxhdy5oYXJ2YXJkLmVkdS8yMDI0LzA3LzA4L2NvbW1vbi1vd25lcnNoaXAtYW5kLWhl=
ZGdlLWZ1bmQtYWN0aXZpc20tYW4tdW5ob2x5LWFsbGlhbmNlLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B30731a96" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">from Zohar Goshen and Doron Levit</a>:</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In equilibrium, common owners exert market power=
 indirectly by delegating control rights to other shareholders through broa=
d implementation of =E2=80=9Cstrong=E2=80=9D governance structures across t=
heir portfolio firms. That is, more firms adopt strong governance under com=
mon ownership. These delegated control rights are then leveraged by activis=
ts, which pressure managers of their target firms to reduce investments. Th=
e aggregate effect of lower investments reduces the demand for labor and lo=
wers wages. Importantly, even though activist hedge funds do not internaliz=
e externalities across firms, the cumulative impact of their interventions =
contributes to anticompetitive outcomes. Effectively, common owners establi=
sh a labor market monopsony without resorting to collusion among firms. Con=
sequently, the symbiotic relationship between common owners and hedge fund =
activists is detrimental to society.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is =
important to note that common owners need not consciously act as a monopson=
y or a cartel. The anticompetitive effects follow naturally from common own=
ers=E2=80=99 push for strong governance. The conventional wisdom praises in=
stitutional investors for strengthening corporate governance as it mitigate=
s agency costs (Jensen and Meckling 1976). And indeed, institutional invest=
ors are consistently pushing toward strong governance structures for public=
ly traded firms. However, this perspective often overlooks the principal co=
sts inflicted by activist hedge funds. Consequently, common owners who push=
 for strong governance and bolster hedge fund activism, might mistakenly at=
tribute the realized positive returns on their portfolios to the benefits o=
f reduced agency costs rather than acknowledging the role of labor monopson=
y at play. In other words, the commonly held naive view that strong governa=
nce unequivocally enhances shareholder value by reducing agency costs could=
 explain the anticompetitive impact of common ownership.</p></blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They are concerned with labor-market competition=
 rather than product-market competition: Their worry is not =E2=80=9Ccompan=
ies with common owners won=E2=80=99t compete on price=E2=80=9D but rather =
=E2=80=9Ccompanies with common owners won=E2=80=99t compete to hire workers=
.=E2=80=9D But their mechanism is=C2=A0<em>governance</em>. Schematically i=
t is something like:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left=
: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Big instituti=
onal investors like =E2=80=9Cgood governance.=E2=80=9D They push companies =
to adopt good governance structures that give shareholders strong rights to=
 supervise managers. Strong governance structures include things like one s=
hare one vote (no dual-class stock), all directors elected every year (no c=
lassified boards), independent board chairs, no poison pills etc.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Good governance is good for activist hedge =
funds: It=E2=80=99s hard to win an activist proxy fight at a company with a=
 staggered board and dual-class stock, but it=E2=80=99s easier at a company=
 with shareholder-friendly governance.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">Activists, in this telling, are bad: They =E2=80=9Cpressure managers o=
f their target firms to reduce investments.=E2=80=9D There is a stereotype =
that activist investors push for short-term financial engineering rather th=
an long-term investments in the business.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">This, in Goshen and Levit=E2=80=99s story, is bad for employees (fewer=
 investments means less demand for workers), but you could tell other stori=
es: =E2=80=9CCompanies with common owners are more vulnerable to activists,=
 so they do more stock buybacks and invest less in their business, so they =
don=E2=80=99t compete as effectively to develop new products,=E2=80=9D for =
instance.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know. But w=
hat I like about this story is that it=C2=A0<em>does </em>reflect how inves=
tors and managers think:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-=
left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Big diver=
sified investors=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>care about good governance. The gian=
t asset managers who own every company can=E2=80=99t necessarily develop st=
rong views on how every company should run its business; they focus on <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36105007.198391/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMjIvZG9lcy1tY=
XJrLXp1Y2tlcmJlcmctb3duLXRvby1tdWNoLW1ldGE_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDcxODI0X01PTkVZU1RV=
RkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNzE=
4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe066012a" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">systemic stewardship</a>, on doing things that work across their portfoli=
o rather than things that are company-specific. And they do tend to have a =
broad systematic view that strong, shareholder-friendly=C2=A0governance is =
good, so all companies should have it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">This story doesn=E2=80=99t rely on managers wanting to reduce competit=
ion, or wanting to work in the economic interests of their diversified shar=
eholders. It relies on managers being scared of activists, or being kicked =
out after losing proxy fights.</li></ol><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsore=
d-content" width=3D"auto" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0">
